{"user_message": {"title": "ADR-005: Token Credit Balance Floor — Stabilization Handoff (1 task, 3 pts)", "content": "## Mode: TEAM HANDOFF (Solution Architect → Dev Clone)\n\nTriage of `medical-bill-negotiator` for the single highest-priority **correctness/robustness** defect. The codebase is well-defended (defensive parsing, idempotent charge/credit/grant, fail-closed token guard). The one place the two `Store` drivers **disagree** — and it touches real money — is the negative-amount `credit()` clawback path.\n\n---\n\n## ADR-005 — Enforce a non-negative balance floor in `credit()`\n*(full record: `docs/adr/ADR-005-credit-balance-floor.md`)*\n\n**Context.** The Polar refund handler calls `credit(userId, -b.tokens, \"refund\", …)` (`src/app/api/polar/webhook/route.ts:51`) with **no zero floor**. Both drivers compute `next = cur + amount` and write it:\n- **PGlite** has `token_accounts … check (balance >= 0)` (`pglite-store.ts:38-39`). Refunding a user who already spent tokens → `next < 0` → CHECK **throws** → webhook (no try/catch around `credit`) returns 500 → **Polar retries forever** (poison-pill).\n- **Firestore (prod)** has no such constraint → balance silently goes **negative** → every future `charge` reads `balance < cost` and refuses forever; later purchases credit on top of the negative.\n\nNeither is correct. A clawback can only reclaim tokens that still exist.\n\n**Decision.** Make non-negative balance an invariant of `Store.credit()`, enforced **identically in both drivers**: clamp the post-credit balance with `next = Math.max(0, cur + amount)`. Positive credits are unaffected; negative credits floor at zero. Ledger still records the requested `delta` and the realized `balance_after`. Idempotency (`(reason, ref)`) unchanged.\n\n**Consequences.** Refund clawbacks safe + identical across drivers; no retry storm; no permanently-negative prod balances; ledger stays a faithful audit log. No schema migration — the PGlite CHECK stays as a backstop the clamp never trips.\n\n---\n\n## Task 1 — Clamp credited balance at zero in both Store drivers · **3 pts**\n\n**WHICH files to modify:**\n1. `src/lib/db/pglite-store.ts` — in `credit()`, change `const next = num(cur.rows[0]?.balance) + amount;` → `const next = Math.max(0, num(cur.rows[0]?.balance) + amount);`\n2. `src/lib/db/firestore-store.ts` — in `credit()`, change `const next = cur + amount;` → `const next = Math.max(0, cur + amount);`\n3. `src/lib/db/store.ts` — update the `credit` doc comment to state the contract: *\"Idempotent credit (de-duped by ref+reason). Negative amounts (refund/clawback) reclaim only what remains; the resulting balance is floored at zero and never goes negative. Returns the new balance.\"*\n4. `tests/store-credit.test.ts` — **new file** (test cases below).\n\n**WHAT the contract must be (exact):**\n- `credit(u, +N, …)` → balance increases by N (unchanged behavior).\n- `credit(u, -N, …)` where `cur >= N` → balance = `cur - N`.\n- `credit(u, -N, …)` where `cur < N` → balance = **0** (not negative, no throw).\n- Idempotency preserved: a second `credit` with the same `(reason, ref)` is a no-op returning the current balance.\n- The ledger row still stores `delta = amount` (the requested value, e.g. `-N`) and `balance_after = next` (the clamped value).\n\n**TEST CASES the engineer must add** (`tests/store-credit.test.ts`, vitest), driving the **real PGlite store in-memory** via the proven pattern — set env before importing, then `getPgliteStore()`:\n```ts\nimport { afterEach, beforeEach, describe, expect, it, vi } from \"vitest\";\n// In each test: vi.stubEnv(\"DB_DRIVER\", \"pglite\"); vi.stubEnv(\"PGLITE_PATH\", \"memory://\");\n// then: const { getPgliteStore } = await import(\"@/lib/db/pglite-store\"); const store = await getPgliteStore();\n// afterEach: vi.unstubAllEnvs(); vi.resetModules();\n```\n1. `credit(+100)` from zero → `getBalance` == 100.\n2. `charge` 30, then refund `credit(-100,\"refund\",ref)` → balance floors at **0**, and the call **does not throw** (this is the regression guard for the CHECK-violation bug).\n3. refund `credit(-40,\"refund\",ref)` when balance is 100 → balance == 60.\n4. duplicate refund with the same `(\"refund\", ref)` → second call is a no-op, balance unchanged (idempotency intact).\n5. ledger assertion: after the floored refund, the latest ledger row has `delta == -100` and `balance_after == 0`.\n*(Each test uses a distinct `userId` so the shared in-memory DB stays isolated; or `vi.resetModules()` between tests to get a fresh PGlite.)*\n\n**HOW to validate (run all three, must pass on your increment):**\n```bash\nnpm run typecheck\nnpm run lint\nnpm run test\n```\nThe Firestore branch is type-checked by `tsc` (firestoreStore must satisfy `Store`); the behavioral test runs against PGlite in-memory.\n\n**WHAT NOT to change (scope boundary — do NOT touch):**\n- Do **not** change `charge()`, `grantSignupTokens()`, or any positive-credit caller behavior.\n- Do **not** alter idempotency logic or the `(reason, ref)` de-dup.\n- Do **not** drop or weaken the PGlite `balance_non_negative` CHECK constraint (keep it as a backstop).\n- Do **not** edit the webhook (`polar/webhook/route.ts`) — the fix lives at the Store layer.\n- Do **not** add `order.created`-vs-`order.paid` logic, Firestore `charge` idempotency, partial-refund logic, or any UI change. Those are logged as future-work, not this release.\n\n**Branch/PR policy:** branch off `main`, open a PR via `gh pr create`, emit `dev-clone.pr.created` + `implementation.completed`. Do not auto-merge.", "content_type": "success", "priority": "normal"}}

